    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5aefe000_b04192e9",
        "filename": "infra-sk/index.bzl",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 8,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-15T13:01:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m a little confused where this file comes from. Is this coming from https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_docker ?\n\nIf so, I don\u0027t really see flatten on their public API (but I do see https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_docker#container_load).\n\nIs there documentation on how to find the git repo or whatever that defines these rules? Can we  cross reference that documentation here?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 8,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 8,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "874d6539860ba34ca19be6c10b925162701d721b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d26f533b_c0369f1b",
        "filename": "infra-sk/index.bzl",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 8,
      "author": {
        "id": 10009
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-15T20:50:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It comes from rules_docker. The @io_bazel_rules_docker prefix is just the name under which said repository was imported in the WORKSPACE file, see https://skia.googlesource.com/buildbot/+/680015361430aeab308abe1b56382640fee091e6/WORKSPACE#3010.\n\nIt\u0027s unclear whether container_flatten is part of the public API due to a lack of documentation. But the fact that container_flatten is re-exported along with other, well documented rules in rules_docker, suggests that it is part of the public API (see [1] and [2]).\n\nIf they ever make breaking changes to container_flatten, then it\u0027s probably best to just fork it. The rule itself is relatively small; it\u0027s just a wrapper around a Go program that does all the heavy lifting.\n\nI chose this rule over any of the better documented ones because most other rules in the rules_docker repository produce .tar files with layered outputs, which means we would have to do the flattening ourselves.\n\n[1] https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_docker/blob/6c29619903b6bc533ad91967f41f2a3448758e6f/container/container.bzl#L28\n[2] https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_docker/blob/e290d0975ab19f9811933d2c93be275b6daf7427/container/BUILD#L158",
      "parentUuid": "5aefe000_b04192e9",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 8,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 8,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "874d6539860ba34ca19be6c10b925162701d721b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e4ea2675_e3af5b22",
        "filename": "infra-sk/index.bzl",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 8,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-16T13:00:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Can we revisit our naming convention for WORKSPACE (assuming those names are something we can freely choose)? If I am looking in this file, I want to have a better impression of which github repo the rules come from.\n\nFor example, we have @build_bazel_rules_nodejs which seems like a fine naming scheme. I\u0027m not quite sure why there\u0027s an io_ in @io_bazel_rules_docker\n\nI\u0027m fine with that being handled in a followup CL.\n\nI would still like a comment at the top of index.bzl pointing to WORKSPACE since it\u0027s not otherwise obvious of that connection.",
      "parentUuid": "d26f533b_c0369f1b",
      "range": {
